'''Varves'''

----

A Varve consists of a distinct layer of silt lying on top of a layer of sand. When composing a geological history of an area, Varve deposits can be used to locate the origins of a lake.

The silt is deposited annually in lakes found close to glaciers. Coarser, lighter coloured silt is deposited during spring when meltwater streams from the glaciers are at their peak discharge and therefore carrying their maximum sediment load. 

The discharge decreases towards autumn - when temperatures begin to drop. This causes meltwater levels fall, and a finer, darker coloured silt will settle. 

Each band of coarse, light coloured material upon fine dark coloured material represents one year's deposition. By counting the number of varves it is possible to date the origin of the lake. Variations in the thickness of each varve will indicate warmer and colder periods (e.g. thick light coloured bands indicate a greater melt water capacity, which is caused by glacial melting).

[[Image:varves.gif|Varves deposited in a glacial lake. A light and dark layer together represents approximately one year. Geologists are able to date ice retreats by counting the varves in lake deposits left behind by the ice]]